I think it’s easy to discount the creative choices an actor comes up with on their own, too. It’s not just parroting lines, it’s discovering ways to make other people feel a specific emotion, usually negotiated between actor, director, and screenwriter. And then doing them twelve times in a row to get all the right angles and also shooting it out of order compared to other scenes, so you have minimal thruline to draw from. Point is, it’s not just emoting, it’s also about making bold choices. (And being judged based on your script rather than your own self; the actress who played Rose in Star Wars 8 never had a chance with a script like that)

That said, when compared to other forms of labor, yeah, there’s a lot of other jobs I’d classify as being much more difficult
